@dnfield Indeed, this is getting messy :/ 

@TheFedex87 
Yeah, I checked on Catalina and it's working *almost* correctly (Xcode 11/iOS 13/flutter stable). SImple `print()` statements don't output anything though. 
But you can circumvent that by using the `logging` package along with the `log()` method from `dart:developer`.

@justinmc would you mind taking a look at scale and pan performance on web / mobile web, especially when text is used? May even be an opportunity for a test/benchmark. I used statsfl (https://pub.dev/packages/statsfl) (to easily benchmark across mobile and desktop web browsers), your above column/row example, and added an appbar to increase the row/column count and disable/enable text. 

On chrome mobile, LG G7 ThinQ, issues are immediately apparent with text enabled and a crash can instantly be induced by scaling. FPS issues with scroll and scale start around 75x75 if text is disabled, jank is severe around 150x150, and crash prone around 300x300.

On chrome with my decently specced PC, an FPS drop can be seen immediately when scrolling with text enable, but scaling can maintain 60fps. At 10x10 scaling performance is impacted, severe at 20x20, and crash prone on anything above 30x30. Without text performance issues start at 20x20, but the issue does not become severe until over 100x100.

`bool _text = true`

```
appBar: AppBar(
        actions: [
          IconButton(
              icon: Icon(Icons.add),
              onPressed: () {
                setState(() {
                  _rowCount += 5;
                  _columnCount += 5;
                });
              }),
          IconButton(
              icon: Icon(Icons.text_fields),
              onPressed: () {
                setState(() {
                  _text = !_text;
                });
              })
        ],
        // Here we take the value from the MyHomePage object that was created by
        // the App.build method, and use it to set our appbar title.
        title: Text(widget.title),
      ),
```
```
                      Container(
                        child: _text
                            ? Text("Column: $_columnCount\nRow: $_rowCount")
                            : null,
                        height: 100,
                        color: row % 2 + column % 2 == 1
                            ? Colors.red.withOpacity(0.5)
                            : Colors.green.withOpacity(0.5),
                      ),
```

This may be related to deeper issues with web, but even testing this with skia, you will still notice performance issues. If it is a deeper issue with web, maybe InteractiveViewer can be a better window to diagnose than previous widgets.

@MichaelReed Would you be able to open a separate issue with these details and the full code for your example?

I appreciate you taking the time to dig into the performance.  I haven't done much optimization for web so there could be some easy improvements to make.  Long term though, I think we're going to need something like and `InteractiveViewer.builder` constructor (similar to [ListView.builder](https://master-api.flutter.dev/flutter/widgets/ListView/ListView.builder.html)) that builds visible content on demand.  That will be the only way to handle very large tables.

Edit: Or maybe this is covered by https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/59775

@justinmc I thought that once the `InteractiveViewer` widget is interacted with, it comes to the front most z index. But from your example I see that it keeps it place z-wise even while interacted with. Thanks for the example (btw dartpad gives an error regarding Stack)

Edit: One confusion I have with naming is why do we have only `ScaleStartDetails` for `onInteractionStart`? 
Afaik there are 3 gestures/interaction that are allowed: Scale, Pan, Rotate(in the future). If we have only one callback for all 3 of them, why is the name ScaleXXXDetails instead of InteractionXXXDetails? Am I missing something?
```
              onInteractionStart: (ScaleStartDetails det){
                print(det.focalPoint.dx);
              },
              onInteractionUpdate: (ScaleUpdateDetails det){
                print(det.scale);
              },
```
Also this example does not print anything when I am pinch zooming on the dartweb by the touchpad.

@aytunch Glad that helped.  I'm not sure about the error, hopefully it's just a problem with dartpad. I don't get the error when running locally in Chrome.

Internally, scale, pan, and rotation are all implemented using GestureDetector's onScale callbacks.  The given `details` should provide all the information you need about the gesture (though you may need to do a little bit of calculation, see https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/43833).

Pinch to zoom on a trackpad doesn't work right now, see https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/63060.  Two finger scroll to zoom should work.
